    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Are School Vouchers the Answer?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Elise D Rosenberg says vouchers are short-term solution to long-term problem, which can be solved by aiding pubic schools with federal funds and letting private schools support themselves (William Safire Aug 31 Op-Ed)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire (''Vouchers Help Blacks,'' column, Aug. 31) is correct in asserting that students using vouchers to attend private school see an improvement in both test scores and overall quality of education. But what happens when we funnel our federal education money into these vouchers? Public schools will worsen, and private schools will eventually face the same problems that plague our public schools today: swelling class size, crowded schools and teacher shortages.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>William Safire (''Vouchers Help Blacks,'' column, Aug. 31) is correct in asserting that students using vouchers to attend private school see an improvement in both test scores and overall quality of education. But what happens when we funnel our federal education money into these vouchers? Public schools will worsen, and private schools will eventually face the same problems that plague our public schools today: swelling class size, crowded schools and teacher shortages.</p>
        <p>Our education problem will only be solved by aiding public schools with federal funds and letting private schools support themselves. Vouchers are only a short-term solution to a long-term problem.</p>
        <p>ELISE D. ROSENBERG  Chicago, Aug. 31, 2000</p>
      </block>
